cating the bug.\r\n-->\r\n\r\nWhile working with atomics on the [`hifive1` BSP](https://github.com/riscv-rust/hifive1) for embedded Rust, I found a weird situation in which a load address exception is triggered.\r\n\r\nI tried this code (simplified version):\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nuse core::sync::atomic::{AtomicBool, Ordering};\r\n\r\nfn main() {\r\n    let flag = AtomicBool::new(false);\r\n    let res = flag.compare_exchange(false, true, Ordering::AcqRel, Ordering::Relaxed);  // throws load access fault exception\r\n    \r\n    assert!(res.is_ok());\r\n}\r\n```\r\nNo compilation errors were triggered.\r\n\r\nI expected to see this happen: the atomic boolean successfully sets its value and the assertion does not panic.\r\n\r\nInstead, this happened: the `compare_exchange` operation threw a load access fault exception at the CPU level.\r\n\r\nIf I substitute the code with this:\r\n```rust\r\nuse core::sync::atomic::{AtomicBool, Ordering};\r\n\r\nfn main() {\r\n    let flag = AtomicBool::new(false);\r\n\r\n    let res = !flag.load(Ordering::Acquire);\r\n    assert!(res);\r\n    flag.store(true, Ordering::Release);\r\n}\r\n```\r\nIt works as expected.\r\n\r\n### Meta\r\n<!--\r\nIf you're using the stable version of the compiler, you should also check if the\r\nbug also exists in the beta or nightly versions.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n`rustc --version --verbose`:\r\n```\r\nrustc 1.71.0-nightly (39c6804b9 2023-04-19)\r\nbinary: rustc\r\ncommit-hash: 39c6804b92aa202369e402525cee329556bc1db0\r\ncommit-date: 2023-04-19\r\nhost: x86_64-apple-darwin\r\nrelease: 1.71.0-nightly\r\nLLVM version: 16.0.2\r\n```\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nInclude a backtrace in the code block by setting `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` in your\r\nenvironment. E.g. `RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo build`.\r\n-->\r\n<details><summary>Backtrace</summary>\r\n<p>\r\n\r\n```\r\n<backtrace>\r\n```\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n</details>\r\n", "closed_by": null, "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/issues/110857/reactions", "total_count": 0, 